[2026-02-02T17:02:21.470Z] [INFO] {
  "type": "user",
  "message": {
    "role": "user",
    "content": [
      {
        "tool_use_id": "toolu_01AiYCAZBJeX7ezjWBJFFzg5",
        "type": "tool_result",
        "content": "     1→# associative-dependent-logic\n     2→\n     3→A prototype for logic framework that can reason about anything relative to given probability of input statements.\n     4→\n     5→## Implementations\n     6→\n     7→This project provides two equivalent implementations:\n     8→\n     9→- **[JavaScript](./js/)** — Node.js implementation using the official [links-notation](https://github.com/link-foundation/links-notation) parser\n    10→- **[Rust](./rust/)** — Rust implementation using the official [links-notation](https://github.com/link-foundation/links-notation) crate\n    11→\n    12→Both implementations pass the same 170 tests and produce identical results.\n    13→\n    14→For implementation details, see [ARCHITECTURE.md](./ARCHITECTURE.md).\n    15→\n    16→## Overview\n    17→\n    18→ADL (Associative-Dependent Logic) is a minimal probabilistic logic system built on top of [LiNo (Links Notation)](https://github.com/link-foundation/links-notation). It supports [many-valued logics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Many-valued_logic) from unary (1-valued) through continuous probabilistic ([fuzzy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fuzzy_logic)), allowing you to:\n    19→\n    20→- Define terms\n    21→- Assign probabilities (truth values) to logical expressions\n    22→- Redefine logical operators with different semantics\n    23→- Configure truth value ranges: `[0, 1]` or `[-1, 1]` (balanced/symmetric)\n    24→- Configure logic valence: 2-valued ([Boolean](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra)), 3-valued ([ternary/Kleene](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-valued_logic)), N-valued, or continuous\n    25→- Use and redefine truth constants: `true`, `false`, `unknown`, `undefined`\n    26→- Resolve paradoxical statements (e.g. the [liar paradox](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liar_paradox))\n    27→- Perform decimal-precision arithmetic (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`) — `0.1 + 0.2 = 0.3`, not `0.30000000000000004`\n    28→- Query the truth value of complex expressions\n    29→- Define dependent types as links — universe hierarchy, Pi-types, lambdas, type queries\n    30→- Combine types with probabilistic logic in a unified framework\n    31→\n    32→## Supported Logic Types\n    33→\n    34→| Valence | Name | Truth Values (in `[0, 1]`) | Truth Values (in `[-1, 1]`) | Reference |\n    35→|---------|------|---------------------------|----------------------------|-----------|\n    36→| 1 | Unary (trivial) | `{any}` (no quantization) | `{any}` (no quantization) | [Many-valued logic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Many-valued_logic) |\n    37→| 2 | Binary / [Boolean](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra) | `{0, 1}` (false, true) | `{-1, 1}` (false, true) | [Classical logic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_logic) |\n    38→| 3 | Ternary / [Three-valued](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-valued_logic) | `{0, 0.5, 1}` (false, unknown, true) | `{-1, 0, 1}` (false, unknown, true) | [Kleene logic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-valued_logic#Kleene_and_Priest_logics), [Łukasiewicz logic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C5%81ukasiewicz_logic), [Balanced ternary](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balanced_ternary) |\n    39→| 4 | Quaternary | `{0, ⅓, ⅔, 1}` | `{-1, -⅓, ⅓, 1}` | [Belnap's four-valued logic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Many-valued_logic) |\n    40→| 5 | Quinary | `{0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1}` | `{-1, -0.5, 0, 0.5, 1}` | [Many-valued logic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Many-valued_logic) |\n    41→| N | N-valued | N evenly-spaced levels | N evenly-spaced levels | [Many-valued logic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Many-valued_logic) |\n    42→| 0/∞ | Continuous / [Fuzzy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fuzzy_logic) | Any value in `[0, 1]` | Any value in `[-1, 1]` | [Fuzzy logic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fuzzy_logic), [Łukasiewicz ∞-valued](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C5%81ukasiewicz_logic) |\n    43→\n    44→## Quick Start\n    45→\n    46→### JavaScript\n    47→\n    48→```bash\n    49→cd js\n    50→npm install\n    51→node src/adl-links.mjs demo.lino\n    52→```\n    53→\n    54→### Rust\n    55→\n    56→```bash\n    57→cd rust\n    58→cargo run -- demo.lino\n    59→```\n    60→\n    61→### Example\n    62→\n    63→Create a file `example.lino`:\n    64→\n    65→```lino\n    66→# Define a term\n    67→(a: a is a)\n    68→\n    69→# Set up operators\n    70→(!=: not =)\n    71→(and: avg)\n    72→(or: max)\n    73→\n    74→# Assign probabilities to axioms\n    75→((a = a) has probability 1)\n    76→((a != a) has probability 0)\n    77→\n    78→# Query probabilities\n    79→(? ((a = a) and (a != a)))   # -> 0.5\n    80→(? ((a = a) or  (a != a)))   # -> 1\n    81→```\n    82→\n    83→Output:\n    84→```\n    85→0.5\n    86→1\n    87→```\n    88→\n    89→## Syntax\n    90→\n    91→### Term Definitions\n    92→\n    93→```lino\n    94→(term_name: term_name is term_name)\n    95→```\n    96→\n    97→Example: `(a: a is a)` declares `a` as a term.\n    98→\n    99→### Probability Assignments\n   100→\n   101→```lino\n   102→((<expression>) has probability <value>)\n   103→```\n   104→\n   105→Example: `((a = a) has probability 1)` assigns probability 1 to the expression `a = a`.\n   106→\n   107→### Range Configuration\n   108→\n   109→```lino\n   110→(range: <lo> <hi>)\n   111→```\n   112→\n   113→Sets the truth value range. Default is `[0, 1]` (standard probabilistic). Use `(range: -1 1)` for balanced/symmetric range where the midpoint is 0.\n   114→\n   115→See: [Balanced ternary](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balanced_ternary)\n   116→\n   117→### Valence Configuration\n   118→\n   119→```lino\n   120→(valence: <N>)\n   121→```\n   122→\n   123→Sets the number of discrete truth values. Default is `0` (continuous, no quantization).\n   124→\n   125→- `(valence: 2)` — [Boolean logic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra): truth values are quantized to `{0, 1}`\n   126→- `(valence: 3)` — [Ternary logic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-valued_logic): truth values are quantized to `{0, 0.5, 1}`\n   127→- `(valence: N)` — [N-valued logic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Many-valued_logic): truth values are quantized to N evenly-spaced levels\n   128→\n   129→### Truth Constants\n   130→\n   131→The symbols `true`, `false`, `unknown`, and `undefined` are predefined with values based on the current range:\n   132→\n   133→| Constant | Default in `[0, 1]` | Default in `[-1, 1]` | Definition |\n   134→|----------|---------------------|----------------------|------------|\n   135→| `true`   | `1`                 | `1`                  | `max(range)` |\n   136→| `false`  | `0`                 | `-1`                 | `min(range)` |\n   137→| `unknown` | `0.5`              | `0`                  | `(max(range) - min(range)) / 2 + min(range)` |\n   138→| `undefined` | `0.5`            | `0`                  | `(max(range) - min(range)) / 2 + min(range)` |\n   139→\n   140→These constants can be used directly in expressions:\n   141→\n   142→```lino\n   143→(? true)              # -> 1 in [0,1], 1 in [-1,1]\n   144→(? false)             # -> 0 in [0,1], -1 in [-1,1]\n   145→(? unknown)           # -> 0.5 in [0,1], 0 in [-1,1]\n   146→(? (not true))        # -> 0 in [0,1], -1 in [-1,1]\n   147→(? (true and false))  # -> 0.5 (avg), 0 (avg in [-1,1])\n   148→```\n   149→\n   150→Truth constants can be **redefined** to custom values:\n   151→\n   152→```lino\n   153→(true: 0.8)           # Redefine true to 0.8\n   154→(false: 0.2)          # Redefine false to 0.2\n   155→(? true)              # -> 0.8\n   156→(? false)             # -> 0.2\n   157→```\n   158→\n   159→When the range changes (via `(range: ...)`), truth constants are automatically re-initialized to their defaults for the new range.\n   160→\n   161→### Operator Redefinitions\n   162→\n   163→#### Binary operator composition\n   164→\n   165→```lino\n   166→(operator: unary_op binary_op)\n   167→```\n   168→\n   169→Example: `(!=: not =)` defines `!=` as the negation of `=`.\n   170→\n   171→#### Aggregator selection\n   172→\n   173→For `and` and `or` operators, you can choose different aggregators:\n   174→\n   175→```lino\n   176→(and: avg)   # Average (default)\n   177→(and: min)   # Minimum (Kleene/Łukasiewicz AND)\n   178→(and: max)   # Maximum\n   179→(and: prod)  # Product\n   180→(and: ps)    # Probabilistic sum: 1 - (1-p1)*(1-p2)*...\n   181→\n   182→(or: max)    # Maximum (default, Kleene/Łukasiewicz OR)\n   183→(or: avg)    # Average\n   184→(or: min)    # Minimum\n   185→(or: prod)   # Product\n   186→(or: ps)     # Probabilistic sum\n   187→```\n   188→\n   189→### Arithmetic\n   190→\n   191→```lino\n   192→(<A> + <B>)   # Addition\n   193→(<A> - <B>)   # Subtraction\n   194→(<A> * <B>)   # Multiplication\n   195→(<A> / <B>)   # Division\n   196→```\n   197→\n   198→All arithmetic uses **decimal-precision rounding** (12 significant decimal places) to eliminate IEEE-754 floating-point artefacts:\n   199→\n   200→```lino\n   201→(? (0.1 + 0.2))             # -> 0.3  (not 0.30000000000000004)\n   202→(? ((0.1 + 0.2) = 0.3))     # -> 1    (true)\n   203→(? ((0.3 - 0.1) = 0.2))     # -> 1    (true)\n   204→```\n   205→\n   206→Arithmetic operands are not clamped to the logic range, allowing natural numeric computation. Clamping occurs only when results are used in a logical context (queries, `and`, `or`, etc.).\n   207→\n   208→### Queries\n   209→\n   210→```lino\n   211→(? <expression>)\n   212→```\n   213→\n   214→Queries are evaluated and their truth value is printed to stdout.\n   215→\n   216→### Comments\n   217→\n   218→```lino\n   219→# Line comments start with #\n   220→(a: a is a)  # Inline comments are also supported\n   221→```\n   222→\n   223→### Dependent Type System\n   224→\n   225→Types are just links — \"everything is a link\". The type system coexists with probabilistic logic.\n   226→\n   227→#### Universe Hierarchy\n   228→\n   229→The type system uses a **universe hierarchy** to avoid paradoxes (like Russell's paradox). Each `(Type N)` is itself a member of `(Type N+1)`:\n   230→\n   231→- `(Type 0)` — the universe of \"small\" types (Natural, Boolean, etc.)\n   232→- `(Type 1)` — the universe that contains `(Type 0)` and types formed from `(Type 0)` types\n   233→- `(Type 2)` — contains `(Type 1)`, and so on\n   234→\n   235→This mirrors the universe hierarchy in Lean 4 (`Type 0`, `Type 1`, ...) and Rocq (`Set`, `Type`, ...). The stratification prevents a type from containing itself, which would lead to logical inconsistency.\n   236→\n   237→In LiNo, universes are declared and automatically stratified:\n   238→\n   239→```lino\n   240→(Type 0)                         # universe of small types\n   241→(Type 1)                         # (Type 0) : (Type 1)\n   242→```\n   243→\n   244→#### Type Declarations\n   245→\n   246→```lino\n   247→# Type definition follows the pattern: (SubType: Type SubType)\n   248→(Natural: (Type 0) Natural)\n   249→(Boolean: (Type 0) Boolean)\n   250→\n   251→# Typed term via prefix type notation: (name: TypeName name)\n   252→(zero: Natural zero)\n   253→(true-val: Boolean true-val)\n   254→```\n   255→\n   256→#### Pi-types (Dependent Products)\n   257→\n   258→```lino\n   259→# (Pi (TypeName varName) ReturnType)\n   260→(succ: (Pi (Natural n) Natural))\n   261→```\n   262→\n   263→#### Lambda Abstraction\n   264→\n   265→```lino\n   266→# (lambda (TypeName varName) body)\n   267→(identity: lambda (Natural x) x)\n   268→\n   269→# Multi-parameter: (lambda (TypeName x, TypeName y) body)\n   270→(add: lambda (Natural x, Natural y) (x + y))\n   271→```\n   272→\n   273→#### Application\n   274→\n   275→```lino\n   276→# Explicit: (apply function argument)\n   277→(? (apply identity 0.7))         # -> 0.7\n   278→\n   279→# Prefix: (functionName argument)\n   280→(? (identity 0.7))               # -> 0.7\n   281→```\n   282→\n   283→#### Type Queries\n   284→\n   285→```lino\n   286→# Type check: (expr of Type) — returns 1 (true) or 0 (false)\n   287→(? (zero of Natural))            # -> 1\n   288→(? (Natural of (Type 0)))        # -> 1\n   289→\n   290→# Type inference: (type of expr) — returns the type name\n   291→(? (type of zero))               # -> Natural\n   292→```\n   293→\n   294→#### Type Hierarchy Example\n   295→\n   296→```lino\n   297→(Type 0)\n   298→(Type: (Type 0) Type)\n   299→(Boolean: Type Boolean)\n   300→(True: Boolean True)\n   301→(False: Boolean False)\n   302→(? (Boolean of Type))            # -> 1\n   303→(? (True of Boolean))            # -> 1\n   304→```\n   305→\n   306→## Built-in Operators\n   307→\n   308→- `=`: Equality (checks assigned probability, then structural equality, then numeric comparison with decimal precision)\n   309→- `!=`: Inequality (defined as `not =` by default)\n   310→- `not`: Logical negation — mirrors around the midpoint of the range (`1 - x` in `[0,1]`; `-x` in `[-1,1]`)\n   311→- `and`: Conjunction (average by default, configurable)\n   312→- `or`: Disjunction (maximum by default, configurable)\n   313→- `+`: Addition (decimal-precision)\n   314→- `-`: Subtraction (decimal-precision)\n   315→- `*`: Multiplication (decimal-precision)\n   316→- `/`: Division (decimal-precision, returns 0 on division by zero)\n   317→\n   318→## Examples\n   319→\n   320→Example `.lino` files are available in both `js/` and `rust/` directories.\n   321→\n   322→### Standard Logic (with avg semantics)\n   323→\n   324→See `demo.lino`:\n   325→\n   326→```lino\n   327→(a: a is a)\n   328→(!=: not =)\n   329→(and: avg)\n   330→(or: max)\n   331→\n   332→((a = a) has probability 1)\n   333→((a != a) has probability 0)\n   334→\n   335→(? ((a = a) and (a != a)))   # -> 0.5\n   336→(? ((a = a) or  (a != a)))   # -> 1\n   337→```\n   338→\n   339→### Flipped Axioms\n   340→\n   341→See `flipped-axioms.lino` — demonstrates that the system can handle arbitrary probability assignments:\n   342→\n   343→```lino\n   344→(a: a is a)\n   345→(!=: not =)\n   346→(and: avg)\n   347→(or: max)\n   348→\n   349→((a = a) has probability 0)\n   350→((a != a) has probability 1)\n   351→\n   352→(? ((a = a) and (a != a)))   # -> 0.5\n   353→(? ((a = a) or  (a != a)))   # -> 1\n   354→```\n   355→\n   356→### Liar Paradox Resolution\n   357→\n   358→The [liar paradox](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liar_paradox) (\"this statement is false\") is irresolvable in classical 2-valued logic. In many-valued logics (ternary and above), it resolves to the **midpoint** of the range — the fixed point of negation.\n   359→\n   360→See `examples/liar-paradox.lino` — resolution in `[0, 1]` range:\n   361→\n   362→```lino\n   363→(s: s is s)\n   364→(!=: not =)\n   365→(and: avg)\n   366→(or: max)\n   367→\n   368→((s = false) has probability 0.5)\n   369→(? (s = false))          # -> 0.5  (50% from 0% to 100%)\n   370→(? (not (s = false)))    # -> 0.5  (fixed point: not(0.5) = 0.5)\n   371→```\n   372→\n   373→See `examples/liar-paradox-balanced.lino` — resolution in `[-1, 1]` range:\n   374→\n   375→```lino\n   376→(range: -1 1)\n   377→\n   378→(s: s is s)\n   379→(!=: not =)\n   380→(and: avg)\n   381→(or: max)\n   382→\n   383→((s = false) has probability 0)\n   384→(? (s = false))          # -> 0   (0% from -100% to 100%)\n   385→(? (not (s = false)))    # -> 0   (fixed point: not(0) = 0)\n   386→```\n   387→\n   388→### Ternary Kleene Logic\n   389→\n   390→See `examples/ternary-kleene.lino` — demonstrates [Kleene's strong three-valued logic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-valued_logic#Kleene_and_Priest_logics) where AND=min, OR=max:\n   391→\n   392→```lino\n   393→(valence: 3)\n   394→(and: min)\n   395→(or: max)\n   396→\n   397→(? (0.5 and 1))          # -> 0.5  (unknown AND true = unknown)\n   398→(? (0.5 and 0))          # -> 0    (unknown AND false = false)\n   399→(? (0.5 or 1))           # -> 1    (unknown OR true = true)\n   400→(? (0.5 or 0))           # -> 0.5  (unknown OR false = unknown)\n   401→(? (not 0.5))            # -> 0.5  (NOT unknown = unknown)\n   402→(? (0.5 or (not 0.5)))   # -> 0.5  (law of excluded middle FAILS!)\n   403→```\n   404→\n   405→In [Kleene logic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-valued_logic#Kleene_and_Priest_logics), the law of excluded middle (`A ∨ ¬A`) is **not** a tautology — this is the key difference from [classical logic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_logic).\n   406→\n   407→## Testing\n   408→\n   409→Both implementations have 170 matching tests:\n   410→\n   411→```bash\n   412→# JavaScript\n   413→cd js && npm test\n   414→\n   415→# Rust\n   416→cd rust && cargo test\n   417→```\n   418→\n   419→The test suites cover:\n   420→- Tokenization, parsing, and quantization\n   421→- Evaluation logic and operator aggregators\n   422→- Many-valued logics: unary, binary (Boolean), ternary (Kleene), quaternary, quinary, higher N-valued, and continuous (fuzzy)\n   423→- Both `[0, 1]` and `[-1, 1]` ranges\n   424→- Truth constants (`true`, `false`, `unknown`, `undefined`): defaults, redefinition, range changes, use in expressions, quantization\n   425→- Liar paradox resolution across logic types\n   426→- Decimal-precision arithmetic (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`) and numeric equality\n   427→- Dependent type system: universes, Pi-types, lambdas, application, type queries, prefix type notation\n   428→\n   429→## API\n   430→\n   431→See language-specific documentation:\n   432→- [JavaScript API](./js/README.md#api)\n   433→- [Rust API](./rust/README.md#api)\n   434→\n   435→## References\n   436→\n   437→- [Many-valued logic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Many-valued_logic) — overview of logics with more than two truth values\n   438→- [Boolean algebra](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra) — classical 2-valued logic\n   439→- [Three-valued logic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-valued_logic) — ternary logics (Kleene, Łukasiewicz, Bochvar)\n   440→- [Łukasiewicz logic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C5%81ukasiewicz_logic) — N-valued and infinite-valued extensions\n   441→- [Fuzzy logic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fuzzy_logic) — continuous-valued logic with degrees of truth\n   442→- [Balanced ternary](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balanced_ternary) — ternary system using {-1, 0, 1}\n   443→- [Liar paradox](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liar_paradox) — \"this statement is false\" and its resolution in many-valued logics\n   444→\n   445→## License\n   446→\n   447→See [LICENSE](LICENSE) file.\n   448→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"
      }
    ]
  },
