    "content": [
      {
        "tool_use_id": "toolu_01AL7QCHqvvtGhUHnyBW9e4e",
        "type": "tool_result",
        "content": "     1→# Architecture\n     2→\n     3→This document describes the internal architecture of **Associative-Dependent Logic (ADL)**, a minimal probabilistic logic framework built on [LiNo (Links Notation)](https://github.com/link-foundation/links-notation).\n     4→\n     5→## Project Structure\n     6→\n     7→```\n     8→.\n     9→├── ARCHITECTURE.md          # This file\n    10→├── README.md                # Project overview, syntax, and examples\n    11→├── LICENSE                  # Unlicense (public domain)\n    12→├── js/                      # JavaScript implementation\n    13→│   ├── package.json\n    14→│   ├── src/\n    15→│   │   └── adl-links.mjs   # Core implementation (~370 lines)\n    16→│   ├── test/\n    17→│   │   └── adl-links.test.mjs  # 122 tests\n    18→│   ├── demo.lino\n    19→│   ├── flipped-axioms.lino\n    20→│   └── examples/\n    21→│       ├── liar-paradox.lino\n    22→│       ├── liar-paradox-balanced.lino\n    23→│       └── ternary-kleene.lino\n    24→└── rust/                    # Rust implementation\n    25→    ├── Cargo.toml\n    26→    ├── Cargo.lock\n    27→    ├── src/\n    28→    │   ├── lib.rs           # Core implementation + 122 tests\n    29→    │   └── main.rs          # CLI entry point (~25 lines)\n    30→    ├── demo.lino\n    31→    ├── flipped-axioms.lino\n    32→    └── examples/\n    33→        ├── liar-paradox.lino\n    34→        ├── liar-paradox-balanced.lino\n    35→        └── ternary-kleene.lino\n    36→```\n    37→\n    38→Both implementations are equivalent: they pass the same 122 tests and produce identical results for all inputs.\n    39→\n    40→## Processing Pipeline\n    41→\n    42→The evaluation pipeline has four stages:\n    43→\n    44→```\n    45→LiNo text → Parse → AST → Evaluate → Results\n    46→```\n    47→\n    48→### Stage 1: LiNo Parsing\n    49→\n    50→**Input:** Raw text in LiNo (Links Notation) format.\n    51→\n    52→**Output:** A list of link strings, where each link is a top-level parenthesized expression.\n    53→\n    54→- **JavaScript:** Uses the official [`links-notation`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/links-notation) parser.\n    55→- **Rust:** Uses the official [`links-notation`](https://crates.io/crates/links-notation) crate.\n    56→\n    57→Lines starting with `#` are treated as comments and skipped.\n    58→\n    59→### Stage 2: Tokenization and AST Construction\n    60→\n    61→Each link string goes through two sub-steps:\n    62→\n    63→1. **Tokenize** (`tokenize_one` / `tokenizeOne`): Splits a link string into tokens (parentheses and words). Also strips inline comments (everything after `#`) and balances parentheses after stripping.\n    64→\n    65→2. **Parse** (`parse_one` / `parseOne`): Converts the token list into an AST (Abstract Syntax Tree). The AST is a recursive structure:\n    66→   - **Leaf nodes:** Strings (symbols, numbers, operators).\n    67→   - **List nodes:** Ordered sequences of child nodes, corresponding to parenthesized groups.\n    68→\n    69→There is no operator precedence; all grouping is explicit via parentheses. For example, `(0.1 + 0.2)` is parsed as a 3-element list `[\"0.1\", \"+\", \"0.2\"]`, and `((0.1 + 0.2) = 0.3)` is parsed as `[[\"0.1\", \"+\", \"0.2\"], \"=\", \"0.3\"]`.\n    70→\n    71→### Stage 3: Evaluation\n    72→\n    73→Each AST node is evaluated recursively by `eval_node` / `evalNode`. The evaluation depends on the node structure:\n    74→\n    75→| Pattern | Meaning | Example |\n    76→|---------|---------|---------|\n    77→| `\"0.5\"` (numeric leaf) | Numeric literal, clamped to logic range | `0.5` |\n    78→| `\"x\"` (symbol leaf) | Symbol prior probability (default: midpoint) | `x` |\n    79→| `(head: rhs...)` | Definition form | `(a: a is a)` |\n    80→| `((expr) has probability p)` | Probability assignment | `((a = a) has probability 1)` |\n    81→| `(range: lo hi)` | Range configuration | `(range: -1 1)` |\n    82→| `(valence: N)` | Valence configuration | `(valence: 3)` |\n    83→| `(? expr)` | Query — returns evaluated truth value | `(? (a = a))` |\n    84→| `(A + B)`, `(A - B)`, `(A * B)`, `(A / B)` | Arithmetic (decimal-precision) | `(0.1 + 0.2)` |\n    85→| `(A and B)`, `(A or B)` | Logical conjunction/disjunction | `(a and b)` |\n    86→| `(A = B)`, `(A != B)` | Equality/inequality | `(a = b)` |\n    87→| `(not X)` | Prefix negation | `(not 0.5)` |\n    88→| `(op X Y ...)` | Prefix operator application | `(and X Y Z)` |\n    89→\n    90→### Stage 4: Output\n    91→\n    92→Only query expressions `(? ...)` produce output. Their evaluated truth values are collected and returned as an array of numbers.\n    93→\n    94→## Environment (`Env`)\n    95→\n    96→The environment holds all mutable state during evaluation:\n    97→\n    98→- **`terms`**: Set of declared term names (e.g., `a` from `(a: a is a)`).\n    99→- **`assign`**: Map from expression keys to assigned truth values.\n   100→- **`symbol_prob`**: Map from symbol names to prior probabilities.\n   101→- **`lo`, `hi`**: Truth value range bounds. Default: `[0, 1]`.\n   102→- **`valence`**: Number of discrete truth levels. Default: `0` (continuous).\n   103→- **`ops`**: Map from operator names to operator implementations.\n   104→\n   105→### Truth Constants\n   106→\n   107→The environment pre-initializes four symbol probabilities based on the current range:\n   108→\n   109→| Constant | Value | Description |\n   110→|----------|-------|-------------|\n   111→| `true` | `hi` (max of range) | Represents the maximum truth value |\n   112→| `false` | `lo` (min of range) | Represents the minimum truth value |\n   113→| `unknown` | `(hi + lo) / 2` (midpoint) | Represents epistemic uncertainty |\n   114→| `undefined` | `(hi + lo) / 2` (midpoint) | Represents lack of definition |\n   115→\n   116→These constants are:\n   117→- **Automatically initialized** when the `Env` is created\n   118→- **Re-initialized** when the range changes (via `(range: ...)` or `_reinitOps`/`reinit_ops`)\n   119→- **Redefinable** by the user via `(true: <value>)`, `(false: <value>)`, etc. (using the existing symbol prior mechanism)\n   120→\n   121→In `[0, 1]` range: `true=1`, `false=0`, `unknown=0.5`, `undefined=0.5`.\n   122→In `[-1, 1]` range: `true=1`, `false=-1`, `unknown=0`, `undefined=0`.\n   123→\n   124→### Clamping and Quantization\n   125→\n   126→All logical results are **clamped** to the range `[lo, hi]` and optionally **quantized** to the nearest discrete level (if `valence >= 2`).\n   127→\n   128→**Quantization algorithm:**\n   129→```\n   130→step = (hi - lo) / (valence - 1)\n   131→level = round((x - lo) / step)\n   132→result = lo + clamp(level, 0, valence-1) * step\n   133→```\n   134→\n   135→This maps continuous values to the nearest of N evenly-spaced levels in the range.\n   136→\n   137→## Decimal-Precision Arithmetic\n   138→\n   139→### The Problem\n   140→\n   141→IEEE-754 floating-point arithmetic produces unexpected results for some decimal operations:\n   142→```\n   143→0.1 + 0.2 = 0.30000000000000004  (not 0.3)\n   144→0.3 - 0.1 = 0.19999999999999998  (not 0.2)\n   145→```\n   146→\n   147→### The Solution\n   148→\n   149→All arithmetic operations (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`) use a **decimal-precision rounding** function that rounds results to 12 significant decimal places. This eliminates floating-point artefacts while preserving meaningful precision:\n   150→\n   151→```\n   152→decRound(x) = round(x * 10^12) / 10^12\n   153→```\n   154→\n   155→**JavaScript implementation:**\n   156→```javascript\n   157→const DECIMAL_PRECISION = 12;\n   158→function decRound(x) {\n   159→  if (!Number.isFinite(x)) return x;\n   160→  return +(Math.round(x + 'e' + DECIMAL_PRECISION) + 'e-' + DECIMAL_PRECISION);\n   161→}\n   162→```\n   163→\n   164→**Rust implementation:**\n   165→```rust\n   166→const DECIMAL_PRECISION: i32 = 12;\n   167→pub fn dec_round(x: f64) -> f64 {\n   168→    if !x.is_finite() { return x; }\n   169→    let factor = 10f64.powi(DECIMAL_PRECISION);\n   170→    (x * factor).round() / factor\n   171→}\n   172→```\n   173→\n   174→### Arithmetic Context\n   175→\n   176→Arithmetic operators evaluate their operands in an **arithmetic context** where numeric literals are **not** clamped to the logic range. This allows expressions like `(2 + 3)` to correctly compute `5`, even though the logic range is `[0, 1]`. Clamping only occurs when the result is used in a logical context (queries, `and`, `or`, etc.).\n   177→\n   178→### Numeric Equality\n   179→\n   180→The `=` operator uses a three-tier comparison:\n   181→\n   182→1. **Explicit assignment:** If a probability has been explicitly assigned to the expression (e.g., `((a = b) has probability 0.5)`), use that value.\n   183→2. **Structural equality:** If the left and right AST subtrees are structurally identical, return `hi` (true).\n   184→3. **Numeric comparison:** Evaluate both sides and compare with decimal-precision rounding: `decRound(left) == decRound(right)`.\n   185→\n   186→This ensures that `((0.1 + 0.2) = 0.3)` evaluates to `1` (true).\n   187→\n   188→## Operators\n   189→\n   190→### Default Operators\n   191→\n   192→| Name | Type | Default | Description |\n   193→|------|------|---------|-------------|\n   194→| `not` | Unary | `hi - (x - lo)` | Negation: mirrors around midpoint |\n   195→| `and` | N-ary | `avg` | Conjunction (aggregator-based) |\n   196→| `or` | N-ary | `max` | Disjunction (aggregator-based) |\n   197→| `=` | Binary | Structural/numeric | Equality |\n   198→| `!=` | Binary | `not(=(...))` | Inequality |\n   199→| `+` | Binary | `decRound(a + b)` | Addition (decimal-precision) |\n   200→| `-` | Binary | `decRound(a - b)` | Subtraction (decimal-precision) |\n   201→| `*` | Binary | `decRound(a * b)` | Multiplication (decimal-precision) |\n   202→| `/` | Binary | `decRound(a / b)` | Division (decimal-precision, 0 on div-by-zero) |\n   203→\n   204→### Aggregators\n   205→\n   206→The `and` and `or` operators can be configured to use different aggregation functions:\n   207→\n   208→| Name | Formula | Use Case |\n   209→|------|---------|----------|\n   210→| `avg` | `sum(xs) / len(xs)` | Default for `and`; average truth value |\n   211→| `min` | `min(xs)` | Kleene AND; pessimistic conjunction |\n   212→| `max` | `max(xs)` | Default for `or`; Kleene OR |\n   213→| `prod` | `∏ xs` | Probabilistic AND (independent events) |\n   214→| `ps` | `1 - ∏(1 - xi)` | Probabilistic sum/OR (independent events) |\n   215→\n   216→Operators are redefinable at runtime via LiNo syntax:\n   217→```lino\n   218→(and: min)       # Switch AND to use minimum\n   219→(!=: not =)      # Define != as composition of not and =\n   220→```\n   221→\n   222→## Key Design Decisions\n   223→\n   224→1. **No operator precedence:** All grouping is explicit via parentheses. This keeps the parser minimal and unambiguous.\n   225→\n   226→2. **Decimal rounding over arbitrary precision:** Using 12-digit decimal rounding instead of arbitrary-precision decimal libraries. This is sufficient for logic/probability use cases and keeps both implementations dependency-free (Rust has zero external dependencies; JavaScript uses only the LiNo parser).\n   227→\n   228→3. **Arithmetic is unclamped:** Arithmetic results are not restricted to the logic range `[lo, hi]`. Clamping only happens when results enter the logical domain (queries, logical operators). This allows natural arithmetic while preserving logic semantics.\n   229→\n   230→4. **Equivalent dual implementations:** JavaScript and Rust implementations are kept in sync with identical test suites (122 tests each), ensuring behavioral equivalence.\n   231→\n   232→5. **Redefinable operators:** All operators can be redefined at runtime, enabling exploration of different logical semantics within the same framework.\n   233→\n   234→## Testing\n   235→\n   236→Both implementations share 122 identical tests organized in these categories:\n   237→\n   238→- **Tokenization** (4 tests): Simple/nested links, inline comments, paren balancing\n   239→- **Parsing** (3 tests): Simple/nested/deeply nested AST construction\n   240→- **Environment** (6 tests): Default ops, custom ops, expression probabilities, range/valence config\n   241→- **Evaluation** (10 tests): Literals, definitions, redefinitions, operators, queries\n   242→- **Quantization** (11 tests): Binary, ternary, 5-level, balanced ranges\n   243→- **Logic types** (35+ tests): Unary through continuous, both ranges\n   244→- **Liar paradox** (6 tests): Resolution across logic types and ranges\n   245→- **Decimal arithmetic** (15 tests): Precision, all four operators, equality comparison, nested expressions, edge cases\n   246→- **Truth constants** (29 tests): Default values in both ranges, redefinition, range change re-initialization, use in expressions, quantization with valence, Env API, liar paradox with truth constants\n   247→\n   248→Run tests:\n   249→```bash\n   250→cd js && npm test       # JavaScript\n   251→cd rust && cargo test   # Rust\n   252→```\n   253→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"
      }
    ]
