        "content": "     1→# associative-dependent-logic — JavaScript\n     2→\n     3→JavaScript implementation of the Associative-Dependent Logic (ADL) framework.\n     4→\n     5→## Prerequisites\n     6→\n     7→- [Node.js](https://nodejs.org/) >= 18.0.0\n     8→\n     9→## Installation\n    10→\n    11→```bash\n    12→cd js\n    13→npm install\n    14→```\n    15→\n    16→## Usage\n    17→\n    18→### Running a knowledge base\n    19→\n    20→```bash\n    21→node src/adl-links.mjs <file.lino>\n    22→```\n    23→\n    24→Or use the npm script:\n    25→\n    26→```bash\n    27→npm run demo\n    28→```\n    29→\n    30→### Example\n    31→\n    32→```lino\n    33→(a: a is a)\n    34→(!=: not =)\n    35→(and: avg)\n    36→(or: max)\n    37→\n    38→((a = a) has probability 1)\n    39→((a != a) has probability 0)\n    40→\n    41→(? ((a = a) and (a != a)))   # -> 0.5\n    42→(? ((a = a) or  (a != a)))   # -> 1\n    43→```\n    44→\n    45→## API\n    46→\n    47→```javascript\n    48→import { run, tokenizeOne, parseOne, Env, evalNode, quantize, decRound } from './src/adl-links.mjs';\n    49→\n    50→// Run a complete LiNo knowledge base\n    51→const results = run(linoText);\n    52→\n    53→// Run with custom range and valence\n    54→const results2 = run(linoText, { lo: -1, hi: 1, valence: 3 });\n    55→\n    56→// Parse and evaluate individual expressions\n    57→const env = new Env({ lo: 0, hi: 1, valence: 3 });\n    58→const ast = parseOne(tokenizeOne('(a = a)'));\n    59→const truthValue = evalNode(ast, env);\n    60→\n    61→// Quantize a value to N discrete levels\n    62→const q = quantize(0.4, 3, 0, 1); // -> 0.5 (nearest ternary level)\n    63→```\n    64→\n    65→## Testing\n    66→\n    67→```bash\n    68→npm test\n    69→```\n    70→\n    71→The test suite includes 170 tests covering:\n    72→- Tokenization, parsing, and quantization\n    73→- Evaluation logic and operator aggregators\n    74→- Many-valued logics: unary, binary (Boolean), ternary (Kleene), quaternary, quinary, higher N-valued, and continuous (fuzzy)\n    75→- Both `[0, 1]` and `[-1, 1]` ranges\n    76→- Liar paradox resolution across logic types\n    77→- Decimal-precision arithmetic and numeric equality\n    78→- Dependent type system: universes, Pi-types, lambdas, application, type queries\n    79→\n    80→## Dependencies\n    81→\n    82→- [`links-notation`](https://github.com/link-foundation/links-notation) — official LiNo parser\n    83→\n    84→## License\n    85→\n    86→See [LICENSE](../LICENSE) file.\n    87→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"
