        "content": "     1→# associative-dependent-logic — Rust\n     2→\n     3→Rust implementation of the Associative-Dependent Logic (ADL) framework.\n     4→\n     5→## Prerequisites\n     6→\n     7→- [Rust](https://rustup.rs/) (edition 2021)\n     8→\n     9→## Building\n    10→\n    11→```bash\n    12→cd rust\n    13→cargo build\n    14→```\n    15→\n    16→## Usage\n    17→\n    18→### Running a knowledge base\n    19→\n    20→```bash\n    21→cargo run -- <file.lino>\n    22→```\n    23→\n    24→Or after building:\n    25→\n    26→```bash\n    27→./target/release/adl <file.lino>\n    28→```\n    29→\n    30→### Example\n    31→\n    32→```lino\n    33→(a: a is a)\n    34→(!=: not =)\n    35→(and: avg)\n    36→(or: max)\n    37→\n    38→((a = a) has probability 1)\n    39→((a != a) has probability 0)\n    40→\n    41→(? ((a = a) and (a != a)))   # -> 0.5\n    42→(? ((a = a) or  (a != a)))   # -> 1\n    43→```\n    44→\n    45→## API\n    46→\n    47→```rust\n    48→use adl::{run, tokenize_one, parse_one, Env, EnvOptions, eval_node, quantize, dec_round};\n    49→\n    50→// Run a complete LiNo knowledge base\n    51→let results = run(lino_text, None);\n    52→\n    53→// Run with custom range and valence\n    54→let results2 = run(lino_text, Some(EnvOptions { lo: -1.0, hi: 1.0, valence: 3 }));\n    55→\n    56→// Parse and evaluate individual expressions\n    57→let mut env = Env::new(Some(EnvOptions { lo: 0.0, hi: 1.0, valence: 3 }));\n    58→let tokens = tokenize_one(\"(a = a)\");\n    59→let ast = parse_one(&tokens).unwrap();\n    60→let truth_value = eval_node(&ast, &mut env);\n    61→\n    62→// Quantize a value to N discrete levels\n    63→let q = quantize(0.4, 3, 0.0, 1.0); // -> 0.5 (nearest ternary level)\n    64→```\n    65→\n    66→## Testing\n    67→\n    68→```bash\n    69→cargo test\n    70→```\n    71→\n    72→The test suite includes 170 tests covering:\n    73→- Tokenization, parsing, and quantization\n    74→- Evaluation logic and operator aggregators\n    75→- Many-valued logics: unary, binary (Boolean), ternary (Kleene), quaternary, quinary, higher N-valued, and continuous (fuzzy)\n    76→- Both `[0, 1]` and `[-1, 1]` ranges\n    77→- Liar paradox resolution across logic types\n    78→- Decimal-precision arithmetic and numeric equality\n    79→- Dependent type system: universes, Pi-types, lambdas, application, type queries\n    80→\n    81→## Implementation Notes\n    82→\n    83→The Rust implementation uses the official [`links-notation`](https://crates.io/crates/links-notation) crate for LiNo parsing. The implementation is a direct port of the JavaScript version and produces identical results for all test cases.\n    84→\n    85→## License\n    86→\n    87→See [LICENSE](../LICENSE) file.\n    88→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"
